segments.text: We're sitting here talking with Mrs. Ruth Mendoza-Ordones, O-R-D-O-N-E-S. Ruth grew up in the John Boniva mines, and that's essentially what we'll be talking about this afternoon.
What year were you born, Ruth?
And the mines, and Gnevers Mines.
And Gnevers Mines, and that was 1927?
Would you tell me the story of how you were born?
I passed in the kind of days my mother and my daddy.
I'm not going to school because my dad and my mother, he don't have no money to send me to school.
Yeah, you were going to tell us a story about the chickens and the lady that helped your mother.
Oh, one of my mother, he started playing with me, and at the time he told me I'm too cheap.
And I put attention to my mother what he told me.
And he said, well, daughter, I tell you this because I don't have no money to pay the doctor to bring you.
And I pay a lady to bring you for two chickens.
So you were a cheap child, only costing two chickens.
Were you ever sick as a child out in the mines?
You were a pretty healthy child.
If you were born in 1927, do you remember about what time you left the mine area?
Do you remember how old you were?
So you lived at the mine site after it was closed down?
Do you remember if your parents had to pay rent while you were living there?
Okay, even while he was working in the mine?
He had a lot of help from Mr. Ginniver.
He had a lot of help?
Mr. Ginniver gave your father a lot of help.
Right, because my daddy's a boss man in the mines.
Would you like to answer the phone?
If your father was a boss man and he worked on
top of the mines, or did he go inside the mines?
So he supervised the actual digging out of the lignite.
As a child, did he ever let you go inside the mines?
Did you like going down in the mines?
Could you describe the house that you lived in?
What kind of furnishings were in it?
And I don't have anything good in the house.
Was it one room or two rooms?
It's two rooms and one little kitchen.
And did you have a table and chairs?
I had one table and two chairs.
Did you have beds or did you sleep on them?
I had two beds, and so he had.
And he had a heater, wood heater.
And how many brothers and sisters did you have in the family?
So there were three children and your father and your mother.
Raffaella Flores and Ruth Mendoza and John Mendoza and Primitiva Mendoza.
Isn't that Primitiva is your mother?
My mother is Mary Mendoza and Joe Mendoza.
What kind of cooking utensils did you have?
Did you and your sisters do the cooking or did your mother?
Yes, because I can cook on too little.
And she cooked inside the house in the kitchen?
Did each family have their own outhouse or
Or was there a communal outhouse?
How far away was that from the line of houses?
And you were telling me the other day when we were walking over the mine site that you had to walk.
I had to get my water to the tanks.
And that place had no water.
Well, what would happen when it hadn't rained in a while?
Yes, everybody come to town and get the water.
And did Mr. Coniver pay for that?
You have to do it your own self.
And do you remember how much it cost to get a barrel of water?
Okay, when your father Joe got up in the morning, would he have breakfast before he went to the mine?
And he took a lunch with him.
What usually did he eat for breakfast, and then what did he eat for lunch?
Well, sometimes my mother, well, he don't have nothing to put in.
Well, he put some business, and he put the lunch, too, because he don't have no more.
Well, when you did have food, what kind of food were you eating?
Well, I mean, some potatoes, and sometimes with my mother, he had some chickens.
And then you would have a dinner in the evening when you came home?
Now, did your father, when he came out of the mines at night, he must have been pretty dirty.
Did he clean up at the house, or did he clean up somewhere else?
Yeah, well, before he came to the house, he cleaned by himself from the mines.
So they had bathing facilities there?
What about you and your sisters and mothers?
Did you have a bathtub or anything like that?
Was there only one for the mine?
I know you were kind of small, but maybe your parents told you this.
How many miners and their families were there at the mine?
The largest number at one time, would you say?
Do you know about how many houses there were?
So that would mean at least 22 families.
OK. Now, were there any bachelors at the Boniva mines?
Did they live in the two-room houses?

live in groups yes sir casino had no place to live i see they didn't have a boarding house right no sir do you remember about when the mines shut down you know for good no sir what what did your father joe do when the mines shut down did he become a farmer or
He come straight to town and find a job, and the job he find it to cut some wood.
And he finish that kind of job, and he started to find a job to picking cotton for the family.
It's one kind of job he do before the mines close.
Before the mines or after the mines?
So you went out and picked cotton?
Now that was only during, you know, August and September, wasn't it?
And what did y'all do the rest of the months of the year when there wasn't any cotton to be picked?
Well, my daddy, he started back to cotton woods for white people.
And, of course, his daughters really couldn't do anything else.
My big sister, well, sometimes he worked for the white people to clean the house, and he pay a dollar a day.
Would she walk to town to do that?
You didn't have any mules or carts or anything?
Did some of the other families have it?
Now, I've heard that some of the miners were able to save money and have cars.
Or did that happen at the Bonita Mines?
Augustine told me that he was a taxi driver.
He started to have a car.
And he buy a new car.
And well, he charged the other Spanish people to take it somewhere else.
And he charged $0.98 to bring it to town.
Were you friendly with the other families in the mining camp?
No, because he didn't have the money to support that kind of parties.
He never had nothing, especially not my family, because it's a big family.
Right, a big family without any brothers.
It's been a hardship because the brothers could have gone out and cut wood with the farmers.
What about the celebrations for Cinco de Mayo and Diaz Ciete?
Well, my daddy is the one who celebrates for all the Spanish people.
He celebrates about four times, and he can't support no more.
And that's why the reason he stopped to do that kind of job.
Do you remember any trips that you ever made to town, to Rock Bay?
Now you said you lived in the mines or in the mining camp until you were 22.
Well, I started myself to work and I started to learn a little bit what I needed myself.
And I worked for too many people.
Well, I started to clean the houses.
And I worked for too many years in that kind of job.
And I started back to work in a cafe, wash dishes.
And that, when I started in a new job, is in a nursing home.
About how old were you when you started in a nursing home?
And I worked four years in a restaurant.
And did you live at the rest home where you worked?
My daddy, he paid some rent over there.
And he continued to chop wood all this time?
Do you do any other kind of odd jobs?

No, it's all the job he do because that's all the job over here right there Did your father was your father and mother were they born here in the United States or no my mother and my daddy he's from Mexico He brought in
Did he come over during the revolution?
So it would have been after 1910 and probably before 1920?
My daddy, he can talk English.
Do you know where they learned English?
Well, my daddy's the one he learned a little bit.
Did your parents leave any relatives in Mexico?
They didn't have just the two of them?
Yes, my daddy and my mother.
Did they ever talk to you about old Mexico?
Well, sometime my daddy, he talked to us.
He said he never going to forget it, the town he lived before.
What did he mean by that exactly?
Why he mean, because it's his own town.
And he said over here in Texas, it's kind of hard when somebody he didn't know to talk English.
Did he ever say that he thought being in Texas was better than being in Mexico?
The thing is hard for him because he can't have a good job.
Because he talked on own language, Spanish.
And over here in Texas, he need a lot of English to have a good job.
But the jobs that he had here in Texas, did they pay better than what he would have had in Mexico?
Well, he said he paid the same.
But he never wanted to go back to Mexico?
He promised he'd never come back to Mexico.
Did he ever give you a reason for that?
Well, he said he liked Texas, and he loved Texas, and he feel more better in Texas.
Glad to see the mine shut down, or was he upset?
No, he's kind of sad when Mr. Guneva caused the mine, because there's no jobs over here in Rockdale.
Were there many other families that were in the same situation?
There's a lot of people he said a little bit, because that's her fault.
Did Mr. Coniver try to help them find jobs?
He did let you live at the camp for free after he left?
Yes, about three months, something like that.
But you and your family stayed at the mining camp?
Did anybody ever come through and tear down all the houses and take them away?
Somebody, I don't know who, he come and get all the houses.
Do you remember about how old you were when that happened?
So you were the only family over there on that road that we saw the other day?
If we could go back to the cooking.
Some people said they cooked inside.
Some people said they had outside stoves.
But my mother, he have a heater to cook.
And we noticed over another mining camp that we visited after you went home the other day,
That there were little brick squares where the houses should be.
Do you have any idea what those were?
Did you build steps or anything like that around the houses?
Well, the Spanish people, he built a lot of things to save some potatoes or save something else.
So did they put bricks around their little gardens?
Did they put little brick patios, for instance, in front of their wood houses?
Did the two-room wood houses have wooden floors, or were they dirt floors?
Sometimes he put it, and sometimes not, because he no help.
This is going to be a weird question.
Do you remember the so-called Great Depression at all?
The way you described it, it seems like you were brought up in a poor family.
So I guess you really don't know what the Great Depression was?
How old, if I could ask this, how old were you when you got married, and how did you meet your husband?
If you don't want to answer, that's all right.
Did you meet him in Rockdale?
No, I miss him in Waco.
He's the hometown of my husband.
He have all the family, all the brothers.
He don't have no father, too.
Did you travel to Waco to see friends?
I have a lot of friends and all the family, my husband.
But how did you get to Waco to meet your husband?
Did you go there for a job?
He worked over here in Rockdale when I met my husband.
And I worked in a nursing home.
And the rest home is possible.
And his father was in the rest home, and that's how you met him?
Did you ever go to the commissary at the Beneath the Mine yourself?
And when she had some credit, she could go over there and buy food?
Mr. Guneva gave it to her.
Did she ever tell you any stories about the commissary?
Well, he told me his story.
My daddy, he worked one day, forget what he needed.
And then you went and got...
Could you describe the clothes that you and your sisters wore?
Were they dresses or were they pants?
Because my mother, he buys our friends that my mother, he gave us a lot of clothes for us.
The friends helped you out with clothes?
Did your mother ever make any clothes?
Yes, sometimes he make it, sometimes not.
Were those houses pretty chilly, pretty cold?
And all you had was that one little stove to keep you warm.
Were there ever any days when the mine was in operation that your father did not work?
Yes, he stayed at home and he'd go back and get some wood for us.
So your father didn't work all year long?
Do you remember the longest period of time that he went without working his mine?
Did Mr. Guinevere provide the heating stove that you had?
Your father had to purchase that?
And he used the wages from the mine.
What did you and your sisters and your mother do while your dad was away during the day?
Staying at home because my mother and my daddy, he didn't let her go nowhere else.
Did your mother take care of the garden?
And was the garden planted right next to your house?
Right in front of it or behind it?
Do you remember what kind of vegetables your mother planted?
before we get into the story of how you and your husband built this marvelous house that you had, I want to ask one more question about the mines.
Most of the miners were from Mexico.
Do you remember any black miners?
Do you ever have a desire to
To go to Mexico, or have you been?
I've been to Mexico, two towns.
And I stay over there about two weeks, me and my husband and my family.
Would you like to go back and visit?
Would you like to live there, do you think?
Let me go ahead and flip the tape so we won't have to do that.
